982
00:57:24.302 --> 00:57:27.982
Our lead program is called SENTI-202, where we've used this logic gate

983
00:57:28.082 --> 00:57:31.242
technology to engineer an off-the-shelf allogeneic NK

984
00:57:31.282 --> 00:57:34.002
product to treat relapse/refractory AML.

985
00:57:35.222 --> 00:57:38.002
Some of the benefits of the logic gating technology is that it allows you to go

986
00:57:38.082 --> 00:57:41.762
after cancers for which there are no clean, single targets available.

987
00:57:42.262 --> 00:57:45.162
We spent many, many years in the field looking for targets that are only on the

988
00:57:45.202 --> 00:57:47.722
cancer cells and minimally expressed on healthy cells.

989
00:57:47.902 --> 00:57:49.922
There's probably only so many of those that are out there.

990
00:57:50.642 --> 00:57:54.392
But if we can use this technology to program cells to recognize multiple

991
00:57:54.482 --> 00:57:58.282
targets and then make a decision on what to kill and what not to kill, perhaps we

992
00:57:58.302 --> 00:58:00.402
can expand the types of indications we can go after.

993
00:58:01.222 --> 00:58:05.202
We were very excited to present back in December at ASH, our results from

994
00:58:05.242 --> 00:58:07.922
our Phase I clinical study in relapse/refractory AML,

995
00:58:08.802 --> 00:58:12.342
where we saw durable responses with a 50%

996
00:58:12.422 --> 00:58:16.122
ORR rate, about 40% CR/CR rate.

997
00:58:17.082 --> 00:58:20.182
One of the nice things about this product is we saw actually evidence of high MRD

998
00:58:20.242 --> 00:58:21.302
negative rates as well,

999
00:58:22.222 --> 00:58:25.502
and a very good safety profile consistent with many of the NK studies that

1000
00:58:26.042 --> 00:58:29.842
previous speakers reported on. I'm going to show you some data also confirming the

1001
00:58:29.922 --> 00:58:33.822
MOA of the product, where you can see selective killing of these AML blasts

1002
00:58:33.862 --> 00:58:37.382
and leukemic stem cells, along with sparing of the healthy bone marrow stem

1003
00:58:37.462 --> 00:58:40.242
cells. So this program did have the fortune of being

1004
00:58:41.362 --> 00:58:44.412
designated with RMAT last year, which gives us some opportunity to interact with

1005
00:58:44.422 --> 00:58:47.672
the FDA more frequently to try to move this program forward, and our plan is to

1006
00:58:47.682 --> 00:58:49.602
launch into a pivotal study later this year.

1007
00:58:50.142 --> 00:58:53.732
We also have a lot of intention to actually use this logic gate technology in other

1008
00:58:53.822 --> 00:58:55.442
cancers, including in solid tumors.

1009
00:58:56.722 --> 00:58:58.132
So we are focused initially on AML.

1010
00:58:58.192 --> 00:59:01.722
We think it's a place where NK's have been tried quite a lot, and we think there's

1011
00:59:01.782 --> 00:59:05.622
opportunities to really bring something new to the treatment of patients with

1012
00:59:05.682 --> 00:59:09.342
AML. Relapse/refractory AML is our initial focus, although we have

1013
00:59:09.642 --> 00:59:12.362
an opportunity, I think, and a lot of clinical interest to move this into the newly

1014
00:59:12.422 --> 00:59:14.382
diagnosed space, which is what our plan is.

1015
00:59:14.882 --> 00:59:17.991
And certainly, as I mentioned earlier, solid tumor is an area that we are very

1016
00:59:18.022 --> 00:59:21.491
excited to try to push forward into. All right.

1017
00:59:21.542 --> 00:59:24.702
So let me tell you a little bit about the underlying genetic technology that we

1018
00:59:24.742 --> 00:59:28.612
developed here at Senti. I'm going to focus today primarily on this idea of logic

1019
00:59:28.612 --> 00:59:32.362
gating. Essentially, what we're doing is building combinations of CAR

1020
00:59:32.442 --> 00:59:36.071
receptors. So on one hand, we can build activating CARs that

1021
00:59:36.102 --> 00:59:39.082
recognize multiple cancer antigens and trigger killing.

1022
00:59:39.822 --> 00:59:43.242
On the other hand, we can build inhibitory CAR receptors, which is what that purple

1023
00:59:43.262 --> 00:59:45.602
receptor is supposed to represent.

1024
00:59:45.622 --> 00:59:49.262
And what that inhibitory receptor does is it can recognize healthy targets,

1025
00:59:49.522 --> 00:59:53.202
so targets that are highly expressed on healthy cells, but not on cancer cells and

1026
00:59:53.262 --> 00:59:55.182
provide a do not kill type of signal.

1027
00:59:56.042 --> 00:59:59.542
This requires a lot of optimization because you have to balance the two arms of the

1028
00:59:59.582 --> 01:00:02.702
CARs, right? If you have an activating CAR that's too strong, you're going to

1029
01:00:02.742 --> 01:00:04.662
trigger killing, and you can't shut it off.

1030
01:00:05.202 --> 01:00:09.102
If the inhibitory CAR is too strong, you might just make the cells energenic,

1031
01:00:09.142 --> 01:00:11.382
and they can't do anything. So you have to balance the two, and there's a lot of

1032
01:00:11.402 --> 01:00:12.542
engineering that goes behind that.

1033
01:00:13.282 --> 01:00:16.242
We do have other technologies that I won't have time to really go through today.

1034
01:00:16.582 --> 01:00:16.842
We are,

1035
01:00:18.802 --> 01:00:22.182
like Dr. Ramy mentioned, very excited about the idea of multi-arming cells.

1036
01:00:22.922 --> 01:00:24.962
We also believe in the need to control

1037
01:00:25.862 --> 01:00:29.692
these multi-arming constructs. So using, for example, small molecule regulators or,

1038
01:00:29.762 --> 01:00:32.342
for example, some of the synthetic promoters that were mentioned earlier to try to

1039
01:00:32.382 --> 01:00:34.242
regulate when and how much of these

1040
01:00:35.542 --> 01:00:37.722
constructs are being expressed, we think are very important.

1041
01:00:39.462 --> 01:00:42.302
So why logic gates, right? So if we think about developing a cell therapy, cell

1042
01:00:42.342 --> 01:00:45.622
therapies are inherently, at least at this stage in time, more complex than a

1043
01:00:45.642 --> 01:00:49.522
biologic drug. So we want to go after diseases for which there's no

1044
01:00:49.562 --> 01:00:51.262
direct biologic competition, right?

1045
01:00:51.402 --> 01:00:55.212
It's oftentimes, from a pharma perspective, easier just to make a protein

1046
01:00:56.102 --> 01:01:00.022
than it is to make a cell. It turns out there are many, many efforts to try to

1047
01:01:00.042 --> 01:01:03.932
develop, as everyone here knows, ADCs, T-cell engagers, et cetera, against

1048
01:01:03.962 --> 01:01:06.942
those targets that have been well-recognized to be clean

1049
01:01:06.982 --> 01:01:10.722
enough to essentially enable that sort of approach.

1050
01:01:10.742 --> 01:01:13.982
But if you can't find such a clean target, one of the risks you see is that you

1051
01:01:14.082 --> 01:01:17.142
have this on-target, off-tumor killing that makes it difficult to find a

1052
01:01:17.162 --> 01:01:21.022
therapeutic window. So we want to go after cancers for which there are no clean

1053
01:01:21.062 --> 01:01:23.982
targets that are available, but by combining two or three targets

1054
01:01:24.022 --> 01:01:27.990
togetherThat signature or that panel can give you the specificity that you

1055
01:01:28.030 --> 01:01:28.250
want.

1056
01:01:29.550 --> 01:01:32.069
So we are doing this for AML, and that's what today I'm going to focus on today.

1057
01:01:33.930 --> 01:01:36.870
So there's a high unmet need in patients with relapsed refractory AML.

1058
01:01:37.630 --> 01:01:41.520
This is a chart here on the left side from Blood, sort of indicating the general

1059
01:01:41.990 --> 01:01:45.970
sort of a matrix by which relapsed refractory AML is treated.

1060
01:01:46.650 --> 01:01:50.460
In general, like many physicians are actually looking for a clinical trial because

1061
01:01:50.490 --> 01:01:53.820
they recognize that many of the existing drugs, even if they're approved, are not

1062
01:01:53.850 --> 01:01:57.350
giving great responses. Number two is patients can be eligible for an

1063
01:01:57.390 --> 01:02:00.970
allogeneic HCT, and depending on whether the answer is yes or no, you

1064
01:02:01.230 --> 01:02:02.970
can qualify for a stem cell transplant.

1065
01:02:03.530 --> 01:02:07.170
However, to get to that stem cell transplant, you need to be able to clear enough

1066
01:02:07.230 --> 01:02:10.050
of the disease so that the patient can go through that process.

1067
01:02:11.570 --> 01:02:15.410
In general, patients can get things like salvage chemotherapy, plus or minus

1068
01:02:15.630 --> 01:02:18.190
venetoclax. There are targeted therapies that are approved.

1069
01:02:18.970 --> 01:02:22.390
But unfortunately, if you don't have some of those mutations, you may not be

1070
01:02:22.430 --> 01:02:23.090
eligible for those.

1071
01:02:24.070 --> 01:02:27.310
Right now, relapsed refractory AML patients have relatively

1072
01:02:28.170 --> 01:02:31.970
sort of poorer prognosis, unfortunately, with CR rates in the 15% to

1073
01:02:32.010 --> 01:02:35.830
20% range, CRch rates in the 20% to 30% range, and the

1074
01:02:35.850 --> 01:02:37.260
median survival is about five months.

1075
01:02:39.130 --> 01:02:42.590
There's a couple of interesting criterias that also make AML a good test case for

1076
01:02:42.630 --> 01:02:46.480
this LogicGate technology. It turns out in AML, responses require two

1077
01:02:46.510 --> 01:02:50.070
major things to happen. So in the middle category here, you have to be able to kill

1078
01:02:50.110 --> 01:02:54.090
the AML blasts. So you have to get the AML blast count below 5%.

1079
01:02:54.570 --> 01:02:57.930
There's this added sort of measurement that people are starting to do around using

1080
01:02:58.010 --> 01:03:01.910
MRD detection to see if you can get down to a sensitivity of 10 to

1081
01:03:01.950 --> 01:03:05.730
minus three or 10 to minus four in terms of determining have I killed the AML

1082
01:03:05.790 --> 01:03:09.710
cells. But there's a second category that's very important, which is looking

1083
01:03:09.730 --> 01:03:13.430
at peripheral blood counts, and that's really intimately tied in with, number one,

1084
01:03:13.490 --> 01:03:16.570
are you clearing the cancer? But two, are you able to protect the healthy cells,

1085
01:03:16.610 --> 01:03:18.410
including the healthy stem cells, from being killed?

1086
01:03:19.110 --> 01:03:22.330
So there's criteria like looking at the neutrophil counts and the platelet counts,

1087
01:03:22.390 --> 01:03:24.770
and if they're above a certain threshold, we call that a CR.

1088
01:03:25.270 --> 01:03:28.400
If there are intermediate recoveries, those are CRhs and CRIs.

1089
01:03:29.050 --> 01:03:33.039
And MLFS is a category of patients that have responded in terms

1090
01:03:33.110 --> 01:03:36.050
of absence of detectable cancer cells.

1091
01:03:36.090 --> 01:03:38.210
However, the peripheral blood counts have not fully recovered.

1092
01:03:40.170 --> 01:03:43.470
So this is important to us because the way we design this product is to try to kill

1093
01:03:43.510 --> 01:03:47.410
the cancer cells, to go after both the AML blasts and the AML

1094
01:03:47.470 --> 01:03:51.169
leukemic stem cells, which are important in disease, but at the same time, to spare

1095
01:03:51.210 --> 01:03:53.150
the healthy hematopoietic stem cells from being killed.

1096
01:03:53.620 --> 01:03:56.510
And so what's the reason why we need that in this disease?

1097
01:03:57.060 --> 01:04:00.110
It turns out that many of the targets that people are very excited about in AML are

1098
01:04:00.170 --> 01:04:03.210
not only expressed on the AML cells, but they're also expressed on some

1099
01:04:03.710 --> 01:04:07.290
population of healthy blood cells, including sometimes the healthy stem cells.

1100
01:04:07.960 --> 01:04:11.730
And so if you hit the cancer cells too hard, you may

1101
01:04:11.790 --> 01:04:14.520
cause a toxicity to the bone marrow.

1102
01:04:15.470 --> 01:04:18.750
So the way we can try to solve this problem is through this concept of the

1103
01:04:18.760 --> 01:04:21.479
activating and inhibitory CAR, that LogicGate I'm talking about.

1104
01:04:22.110 --> 01:04:25.120
So what we did here was to design an activating CAR to go after two different

1105
01:04:25.150 --> 01:04:28.350
targets that are well-known in the space. These are CD33 and FLT3.

1106
01:04:29.070 --> 01:04:30.270
These were chosen through a pretty

1107
01:04:31.210 --> 01:04:34.510
wide bioinformatic search that we did to look at combinations of targets that might

1108
01:04:34.570 --> 01:04:38.440
go well together. CD33 is very well expressed on AML blasts,

1109
01:04:38.950 --> 01:04:42.710
has some expression on leukemic stem cells, and FLT3 has good expression on

1110
01:04:43.390 --> 01:04:47.250
leukemic stem cells as well. So by putting them together, we think we can more

1111
01:04:47.390 --> 01:04:51.110
broadly and perhaps deeply kill both those cell populations.

1112
01:04:51.690 --> 01:04:55.250
Now it turns out, especially for FLT3, FLT3 has a problem that it's expressed on

1113
01:04:55.270 --> 01:04:58.650
healthy bone marrow stem cells, including the hematopoietic stem cell.

1114
01:04:59.080 --> 01:05:02.710
And so to try to protect those cells from being killed, we did a bioinformatic

1115
01:05:02.750 --> 01:05:06.710
search to look for targets that were expressed on the healthy cells but have low

1116
01:05:06.750 --> 01:05:09.810
expression on the cancer cells. And there happened to be a list of about seven

1117
01:05:09.820 --> 01:05:12.680
targets that came out of that search that were on the cell surface that we could

1118
01:05:12.710 --> 01:05:15.950
address. We went through a whole design process to try to pick out which ones we

1119
01:05:15.990 --> 01:05:19.410
want to go after and selected this target called EMCN or endomucin.

1120
01:05:19.530 --> 01:05:22.590
So endomucin is this target that's got this inverse expression.

1121
01:05:22.650 --> 01:05:25.590
It's high on this particular population of healthy cells and low on the cancer

1122
01:05:25.630 --> 01:05:28.810
cells. And what we did was design an inhibitory CAR to

1123
01:05:28.890 --> 01:05:32.419
recognize that particular target and to shut down the killing activity.

1124
01:05:33.030 --> 01:05:35.880
There's a lot of underlying protein engineering that I'm not going to go through

1125
01:05:35.950 --> 01:05:39.370
here in detail, but getting these two receptors to be balanced was very important.

1126
01:05:40.010 --> 01:05:43.370
Now, the third element here is an IL-15 molecule that we put into the cells to

1127
01:05:43.389 --> 01:05:47.230
enhance the activity. Now, given that this is an NK panel, one might ask,

1128
01:05:47.410 --> 01:05:50.950
does this technology work only in NK cells, or can we get it to work in other cell

1129
01:05:50.970 --> 01:05:53.470
types, and why did we choose NK cells here?

1130
01:05:53.510 --> 01:05:57.430
We do have the LogicGate technology working in both NK cells and T cells.

1131
01:05:57.580 --> 01:06:01.450
And our perspective is we choose the cell type that we think will be best fitted

1132
01:06:01.490 --> 01:06:03.570
for that particular clinical population.

1133
01:06:03.810 --> 01:06:07.390
In AML, one of the challenges for autologous T cells is that oftentimes these

1134
01:06:07.510 --> 01:06:08.510
patients may not have

1135
01:06:09.410 --> 01:06:10.950
been through multiple rounds of treatment.

1136
01:06:11.170 --> 01:06:14.790
Chemotherapy can be toxic to those cells, and even the disease itself may cause T

1137
01:06:14.830 --> 01:06:18.730
cell dysfunction. So getting high-quality autologous CAR T

1138
01:06:18.790 --> 01:06:22.470
from these patients made and delivered back to these patients, which can take a

1139
01:06:22.510 --> 01:06:24.550
month or more, is a major challenge.

1140
01:06:24.890 --> 01:06:28.430
In contrast, NK cells, we can make off the shelf from healthy donors.

1141
01:06:28.440 --> 01:06:32.290
We've developed a very scalable GMP process that allows us to manufacture and

1142
01:06:32.310 --> 01:06:35.860
freeze the cells, and then we can ship the cells out the next day to be used in

1143
01:06:35.890 --> 01:06:39.490
patients. So we think the NK chassis makes a lot of sense.

1144
01:06:39.550 --> 01:06:42.830
In addition to that, there's a lot of clinical literature on the use of natural NK

1145
01:06:42.870 --> 01:06:46.570
cells in the past in humans to try to treat diseases like AML.

1146
01:06:48.030 --> 01:06:50.780
So like I mentioned, we have a 14-day manufacturing process.

1147
01:06:50.870 --> 01:06:53.860
We do get healthy blood from

1148
01:06:55.070 --> 01:06:58.970
selected donors. We do some donor characteristic testing to make sure

1149
01:06:58.990 --> 01:07:02.890
that we are getting samples, and then we can repeatedly get samples from these

1150
01:07:03.430 --> 01:07:06.990
donors that give us high-quality NK cells, both in terms of ability to get the

1151
01:07:07.010 --> 01:07:10.690
cells to expand, but also to maintain high cytotoxicity.

1152
01:07:10.820 --> 01:07:14.630
We use an engineering step. We're using a retrovirus, to deliver the genetic

1153
01:07:14.670 --> 01:07:18.250
circuit. It has three different genes that are encoded on a single virus into the

1154
01:07:18.270 --> 01:07:21.370
cells. We can expand the cells further, and then importantly, we spend a lot of

1155
01:07:21.390 --> 01:07:24.690
time doing cryopreservation to try to preserve the NK cells and make sure they're

1156
01:07:24.750 --> 01:07:28.710
stable so that upon delivery to the clinical site, it's a simple thaw and infuse

1157
01:07:28.730 --> 01:07:32.722
step.The clinical trial currently has been carried out in

1158
01:07:32.762 --> 01:07:35.482
the US as well as in Australia. So we've been able to ship these cells around the

1159
01:07:35.502 --> 01:07:38.782
country, also over to Australia as well for delivery.

1160
01:07:39.922 --> 01:07:43.192
The Phase 1 clinical trial was designed to go after adult

1161
01:07:43.282 --> 01:07:47.262
patients with relapsed refractory AML that expressed either CD33

1162
01:07:47.282 --> 01:07:51.092
or FLT3. It turns out in AML, CD33 is one of the

1163
01:07:51.122 --> 01:07:54.882
diagnostic criteria or in the diagnostic panel, so all of our patients come in

1164
01:07:54.962 --> 01:07:58.722
CD33 positive by clinical site, and then we have some

1165
01:07:58.762 --> 01:08:01.122
data around some patients that are FLT3 positive, some patients that have

1166
01:08:01.162 --> 01:08:02.382
intermediate FLT3 expression.

1167
01:08:04.282 --> 01:08:07.742
We started off the Phase 1 clinical study through a dose-finding to look at

1168
01:08:08.162 --> 01:08:11.962
different schedules of dosing as well as dose escalation, also looking at efficacy

1169
01:08:11.982 --> 01:08:12.622
at the same time.

1170
01:08:14.142 --> 01:08:17.102
So generally, the protocol was for looking at

1171
01:08:17.802 --> 01:08:20.963
this product was to, on the upper left-hand side, look at two different dosing

1172
01:08:21.083 --> 01:08:23.922
schedules. We start out with a lymphodepletion step, like with other cell

1173
01:08:23.942 --> 01:08:27.663
therapies. In this case, we are using fludarabine and cytarabine, which is an

1174
01:08:27.722 --> 01:08:30.482
AML-specific regimen. We tested two different

1175
01:08:31.482 --> 01:08:35.302
dosing schedules in each cycle. The schedule one was once

1176
01:08:35.503 --> 01:08:39.222
every week, so 0, 7, 14. Schedule two was every three or four

1177
01:08:39.282 --> 01:08:42.312
days. So day 0, 3, 7, 10, 14. So five doses total.

1178
01:08:42.802 --> 01:08:44.952
In both cases, we assess for response at 28 days.

1179
01:08:45.463 --> 01:08:48.482
Patients can get up to four cycles, although as you'll see in the Phase 1 study,

1180
01:08:48.562 --> 01:08:50.602
patients generally got one or two cycles at most.

1181
01:08:51.463 --> 01:08:54.942
We did do dose-finding and looked at either one billion CAR positive NK cells per

1182
01:08:55.003 --> 01:08:58.623
dose or 1.5 billion. Ended up going with schedule one.

1183
01:08:58.842 --> 01:09:00.402
It's much more convenient for patients.

1184
01:09:00.652 --> 01:09:04.322
We do want this to be accessible for delivery in infusion

1185
01:09:04.362 --> 01:09:07.742
centers and even be used in potentially outpatient settings.

1186
01:09:08.862 --> 01:09:11.182
And we didn't see any reduced efficacy with schedule one.

1187
01:09:11.543 --> 01:09:14.623
We did use the dose level two. We did see some benefits with that particular

1188
01:09:14.642 --> 01:09:15.003
approach.

1189
01:09:16.102 --> 01:09:19.882
This trial did enroll patients with multiple baseline adverse risk

1190
01:09:19.902 --> 01:09:23.452
characteristics and poor prognosis, especially in the dose level two category in

1191
01:09:23.463 --> 01:09:27.392
these AML patients. We had many patients that actually came with

1192
01:09:27.402 --> 01:09:29.862
baseline low neutrophil counts and low platelet counts.

1193
01:09:29.882 --> 01:09:33.782
Those are typically signs that the patient is not in great shape because the

1194
01:09:33.822 --> 01:09:36.762
disease is somehow causing bone marrow dysfunction in these

1195
01:09:36.782 --> 01:09:40.722
patients. Majority of patients were also diagnosed as adverse

1196
01:09:40.822 --> 01:09:44.512
risk by ELN 2022, which is a diagnostic criteria for stratifying

1197
01:09:44.562 --> 01:09:47.062
patients. These patients were heavily pre-treated.

1198
01:09:47.163 --> 01:09:51.003
One of the criteria is that these patients had to go anywhere between one to

1199
01:09:51.043 --> 01:09:54.902
three prior lines of treatment. If they were eligible for a TARID

1200
01:09:54.942 --> 01:09:57.942
inhibitor, they must have received it and failed it to come on.

1201
01:09:58.342 --> 01:10:01.502
And so you can see that in general, all of our patients received chemotherapy,

1202
01:10:01.562 --> 01:10:04.782
including prior exposure to fludarabine and cytarabine.

1203
01:10:05.372 --> 01:10:09.322
Most patients received venetoclax, hypomethylating agents, and many

1204
01:10:09.362 --> 01:10:12.262
patients actually had prior stem cell transplants and relapsed.

1205
01:10:12.942 --> 01:10:16.812
Also, in the RPTD cohort, a majority of patients were actually refractory to their

1206
01:10:17.202 --> 01:10:20.062
most recent regimen, which means that the last thing that they tried essentially

1207
01:10:20.102 --> 01:10:22.002
didn't work for over less than three months.

1208
01:10:23.802 --> 01:10:26.502
I mentioned most patients got one or two cycles.

1209
01:10:26.562 --> 01:10:29.242
In general, nobody discontinued treatment due to adverse events.

1210
01:10:29.262 --> 01:10:33.102
The reason why in some cases we had patients get one cycle is we got them into an

1211
01:10:33.142 --> 01:10:36.742
MRD negative CR. Physicians got really excited and took them to transplant.

1212
01:10:38.522 --> 01:10:42.282
In general, in terms of overall adverse events, majority of the

1213
01:10:42.342 --> 01:10:46.232
adverse events were essentially attributed not to 202, but to some other element of

1214
01:10:46.232 --> 01:10:47.602
the protocol, including lymphodepletion.

1215
01:10:47.662 --> 01:10:51.462
As we know, lymphodepletion, that can reduce your blood counts, and we did

1216
01:10:51.562 --> 01:10:55.282
see some patients that were reported to have febrile neutropenia, low platelet

1217
01:10:55.422 --> 01:10:57.261
counts, anemia, or thrombocytopenia.

1218
01:10:57.322 --> 01:11:01.182
These are AEs that typically AML docs are very well suited to try to treat and were

1219
01:11:01.192 --> 01:11:03.702
not directly generally attributed to SENTI 202.

1220
01:11:04.542 --> 01:11:08.362
In terms of 202-related AEs, this is, I think, very consistent with prior NK

1221
01:11:08.482 --> 01:11:10.542
clinical studies. NK cells tend to be very safe.

1222
01:11:10.622 --> 01:11:14.502
They don't generate the same level of CRS that you see with CAR T cells.

1223
01:11:15.302 --> 01:11:19.092
Generally what we saw was Grade 1, 2 pyrexia, well managed with standard of care.

1224
01:11:19.122 --> 01:11:20.702
We looked at a whole panel of cytokines.

1225
01:11:20.742 --> 01:11:22.842
The upper right-hand corner here just takes a snapshot.

1226
01:11:23.202 --> 01:11:26.542
But if we look at, for example, IL-6 production, we are way lower than what you

1227
01:11:26.682 --> 01:11:30.262
typically see with a CAR T cell. And we think this is one of the reasons, as

1228
01:11:30.282 --> 01:11:33.902
mentioned earlier, that NK cells can give you a much better safety profile compared

1229
01:11:33.922 --> 01:11:37.502
to T cell-based products. We're excited to see that about

1230
01:11:37.622 --> 01:11:40.822
50% of our patients achieved an overall response with a

1231
01:11:40.862 --> 01:11:44.782
CR/CRh rate in the 30% to 40% range, depending on which patient cohort we looked

1232
01:11:44.842 --> 01:11:48.681
at. One of the things that stood out to us in this trial was that a

1233
01:11:48.722 --> 01:11:52.622
lot of patients, vast majority of patients, whether you were CR, CRh, or even

1234
01:11:52.722 --> 01:11:56.442
MLFS, did get into MRD negative status, which was very

1235
01:11:56.462 --> 01:12:00.062
exciting to see. That potentially can correlate with better responses.

1236
01:12:01.362 --> 01:12:05.292
We had a median duration of composite CRs about 7.6 months,

1237
01:12:05.342 --> 01:12:08.882
which again, compares favorably to other drugs in this patient

1238
01:12:08.922 --> 01:12:09.602
population.

1239
01:12:10.482 --> 01:12:12.562
So in general, this is the graph from the top.

1240
01:12:13.702 --> 01:12:16.832
All the responders are on the top. This data is actually from October, so these

1241
01:12:16.842 --> 01:12:19.902
patients, we do have updates that we'll share later this year.

1242
01:12:20.002 --> 01:12:23.302
We had several patients that have survived for close to two years now.

1243
01:12:23.582 --> 01:12:25.222
And we're excited to see many of these patients.

1244
01:12:25.602 --> 01:12:27.142
Some of them go to transplant, as mentioned earlier.

1245
01:12:27.782 --> 01:12:31.022
Doctors are consolidating with that, although that's not necessarily required by

1246
01:12:31.062 --> 01:12:34.202
the protocol per se. And we do envision as we go into the pivotal trial, we'll

1247
01:12:34.262 --> 01:12:37.562
enroll sort of a broader cohort of patients, some that are transplant eligible,

1248
01:12:38.242 --> 01:12:40.702
some that are transplant ineligible, and we'll be able to take a look at the

1249
01:12:40.722 --> 01:12:41.302
differences here.

1250
01:12:42.902 --> 01:12:46.522
Just to get into the MOA in a little bit more detail, we worked with MD

1251
01:12:46.602 --> 01:12:49.582
Anderson, where we sent all our patient samples there, and they actually did CyTOF

1252
01:12:49.602 --> 01:12:53.522
analysis to look at specific subsets of cells in the patient bone marrows.

1253
01:12:54.182 --> 01:12:58.042
So we looked at initially the cancer cells, so the AML blasts and AML leukemic stem

1254
01:12:58.122 --> 01:13:01.612
cells. On the left-hand side, we first looked at the leukemic stem cell population.

1255
01:13:01.642 --> 01:13:05.072
It turns out the majority of these cells are in that G0 quiescent state,

1256
01:13:05.502 --> 01:13:08.442
very difficult to kill with conventional chemotherapy, and that's really consistent

1257
01:13:08.452 --> 01:13:11.202
with prior literature describing this cell population.

1258
01:13:12.182 --> 01:13:15.542
We were very excited to see on the right-hand side actually that with treatment,

1259
01:13:16.602 --> 01:13:19.622
especially obviously for those patients that responded, we saw a significant

1260
01:13:19.642 --> 01:13:23.602
reduction in these LSCs with treatment, sometimes more than tenfold

1261
01:13:23.642 --> 01:13:25.572
or 100-fold, even higher than that,

1262
01:13:26.762 --> 01:13:30.002
giving us some evidence that we are killing those LSCs directly.

1263
01:13:30.042 --> 01:13:33.602
We also see very significant reductions in AML blasts in our responders in the

1264
01:13:33.642 --> 01:13:34.082
middle here.

1265
01:13:34.962 --> 01:13:37.582
Some patients even coming in with over 90% bone marrow blast at

1266
01:13:37.602 --> 01:13:41.143
baseline.Now, the flip side of this is we want to be able to see we're not killing

1267
01:13:41.194 --> 01:13:44.244
the hematopoietic stem cell. So we did the same CyTOF analysis, right, and looked

1268
01:13:44.314 --> 01:13:44.794
at healthy

1269
01:13:45.654 --> 01:13:48.894
samples at the same time. On the right-hand side, the interesting thing is, in

1270
01:13:48.934 --> 01:13:52.804
general, we see compared from baseline to after cycle one or cycle two,

1271
01:13:53.534 --> 01:13:57.094
a maintenance or enrichment of the hematopoietic stem cell

1272
01:13:57.314 --> 01:13:58.834
population, which is exciting to see.

1273
01:13:59.594 --> 01:14:01.034
The left-hand side actually shows

1274
01:14:01.834 --> 01:14:05.154
an interesting finding. We had some patients that did generate a

1275
01:14:05.234 --> 01:14:09.014
CR/CRh response. Remember I mentioned earlier that response requires some of your

1276
01:14:09.034 --> 01:14:12.514
healthy cells to recover. We also had a couple of patients that actually had an

1277
01:14:12.594 --> 01:14:16.154
MLFS response. Again, that response criteria is patients who have

1278
01:14:16.174 --> 01:14:20.154
reduction in tumor counts or undetectable levels of remaining AML

1279
01:14:20.194 --> 01:14:22.074
cells, but you don't get that full recovery.

1280
01:14:22.134 --> 01:14:24.974
You don't even get partial recovery of their healthy cell.

1281
01:14:25.534 --> 01:14:29.274
And it turns out that those two patients came onto the study with basically

1282
01:14:29.284 --> 01:14:31.714
undetectable levels of hematopoietic stem cells

1283
01:14:32.554 --> 01:14:36.174
in the CyTOF analysis. So it does suggest to us perhaps that if patients are coming

1284
01:14:36.234 --> 01:14:40.014
on with poor bone marrow function, you can't rescue something that's not there.

1285
01:14:40.354 --> 01:14:44.314
But perhaps as we try to push this product into earlier lines of therapy, even

1286
01:14:44.354 --> 01:14:48.054
to newly diagnosed AML, we hope we'll see more patients derive benefit from the

1287
01:14:48.074 --> 01:14:49.034
Logic Gate technology.

1288
01:14:50.034 --> 01:14:53.574
The last thing I'll show you from the clinical data here is that in terms of

1289
01:14:54.374 --> 01:14:58.114
platelet counts and neutrophils, you can see, from day minus seven to day zero,

1290
01:14:58.514 --> 01:15:00.934
where you have that lymphodepletion, that's where you see the drops in the

1291
01:15:00.954 --> 01:15:04.474
platelets and the neutrophils. We do have treatment with the product in about 14

1292
01:15:04.494 --> 01:15:07.764
days, from day zero to day 14, and you see a pretty strong recovery, actually, of

1293
01:15:07.854 --> 01:15:11.674
platelets and neutrophils in those responders, indicating that these cells

1294
01:15:11.734 --> 01:15:15.504
aren't causing overt bone marrow toxicity, and perhaps by treating the

1295
01:15:15.514 --> 01:15:18.774
cancer, we're creating the ability for the repopulation of these healthy cells.

1296
01:15:18.934 --> 01:15:20.994
So we're really excited to see that for these patients.

1297
01:15:22.894 --> 01:15:25.774
I lied to you. There's one more piece of data. There is PK data here.

1298
01:15:25.994 --> 01:15:28.184
Generally, we're seeing about 14 to 21 days

1299
01:15:29.014 --> 01:15:31.914
post-lymphodepletion. I think that's what is expected for allogeneic cell therapy

1300
01:15:31.954 --> 01:15:35.594
of this type. We aren't doing any specific editing at this point to try to remove

1301
01:15:35.654 --> 01:15:36.834
factors that might improve

1302
01:15:37.754 --> 01:15:38.314
the allo

1303
01:15:39.514 --> 01:15:41.684
lifespan, although that's something you can certainly think of for a next

1304
01:15:41.714 --> 01:15:42.474
generation product.

1305
01:15:44.114 --> 01:15:47.894
So we're very excited about where SENTI 202 is, and we think it demonstrates

1306
01:15:47.914 --> 01:15:49.094
preliminary promising efficacy.

1307
01:15:49.174 --> 01:15:52.434
I guess this is just a summary, so I'll skip forward just because of time.

1308
01:15:52.474 --> 01:15:56.214
Our plan for this year is to have that next stage interaction with the FDA.

1309
01:15:56.294 --> 01:16:00.274
We do have RMAT status, and we want to get alignment with the FDA on what the plan

1310
01:16:00.294 --> 01:16:01.734
is to move this into the pivotal study.

1311
01:16:02.474 --> 01:16:06.094
There were some recent approvals in the

1312
01:16:06.134 --> 01:16:09.954
relapsed/refractory AML space with single-arm studies with breakthrough

1313
01:16:09.994 --> 01:16:13.334
status given. We think there's a great opportunity for these cells, especially if

1314
01:16:13.354 --> 01:16:17.234
we can maintain this type of response rate and the deep MRD negative

1315
01:16:17.274 --> 01:16:19.754
type responses for this program to move into a pivotal study.

1316
01:16:19.854 --> 01:16:22.594
So that's really what we're focused on at the same time of upgrading our

1317
01:16:22.634 --> 01:16:24.604
manufacturing to be ready for that pivotal.

1318
01:16:25.923 --> 01:16:28.634
The last thing I'll show you is just some videos because I think it's kind of

1319
01:16:28.654 --> 01:16:30.654
exciting to see these logic gates actually in action.

1320
01:16:31.134 --> 01:16:35.054
We have been developing logic gates that can be applied to solid tumors, including

1321
01:16:35.114 --> 01:16:36.214
targets like CEA,

1322
01:16:37.014 --> 01:16:40.894
where CEA is expressed not just on cancer cells, but it has expression on healthy

1323
01:16:40.934 --> 01:16:44.064
colon cells, for example. So we went through the same discovery process and

1324
01:16:44.114 --> 01:16:47.814
identified a healthy target, in this case called VSIG2, that can

1325
01:16:47.834 --> 01:16:50.014
protect healthy cells from being killed.

1326
01:16:50.474 --> 01:16:53.754
We have put this into both NK cells and T cells, and these are microscopy images

1327
01:16:54.114 --> 01:16:57.774
that showcase how we do the development here internally.

1328
01:16:58.374 --> 01:17:02.314
So for the first example, we've mixed the cancer cells in red and the healthy cells

1329
01:17:02.334 --> 01:17:04.854
in green. The healthy cells and cancer cells both express CEA.

1330
01:17:04.914 --> 01:17:07.834
The only difference is the green cells express VSIG2 also.

1331
01:17:08.494 --> 01:17:11.074
And you can see with no NK cells, both these cell populations grow.

1332
01:17:11.874 --> 01:17:14.874
With CEA only targeted NK cells, you kill both.

1333
01:17:15.634 --> 01:17:19.514
And with the CEA not VSIG2, you can basically kill the cancer cells and spare the

1334
01:17:19.534 --> 01:17:20.034
healthy ones.

1335
01:17:20.854 --> 01:17:23.833
I will say that we've done this for T cells as well.

1336
01:17:23.934 --> 01:17:27.234
So, we have this technology working across different cell types.

1337
01:17:27.934 --> 01:17:31.454
We use slightly different protein domains to get it to work in T cells versus NK

1338
01:17:31.494 --> 01:17:33.474
cells, but in general, the principle is the same.

1339
01:17:34.434 --> 01:17:38.254
So with that, I think I'm on time. I would like to thank you for your time.

1340
01:17:38.294 --> 01:17:41.694
Happy to take any questions and yeah, appreciate the opportunity. Thank you.

1341
01:17:45.214 --> 01:17:46.914
Yes. Question, exactly on time.

1342
01:17:47.874 --> 01:17:50.994
Very thoughtful and interesting concept.

1343
01:17:51.814 --> 01:17:53.944
Thank you for this clear presentation.

1344
01:17:54.994 --> 01:17:56.254
Could you elaborate

1345
01:17:57.074 --> 01:18:00.934
a little bit more on how you secure

1346
01:18:00.974 --> 01:18:04.174
that your CAR engineer cells can

1347
01:18:05.254 --> 01:18:09.194
bind when only two or three anchor are being expressed

1348
01:18:09.254 --> 01:18:11.394
and not when there is only one?

1349
01:18:12.294 --> 01:18:14.984
Are there any kind of engineering being- Yeah ...

1350
01:18:14.984 --> 01:18:18.744
made on the receptor? So we're not

1351
01:18:18.774 --> 01:18:22.414
relying on binding per se. It's really the signaling that's giving us

1352
01:18:22.494 --> 01:18:26.354
this logic gating capability. So the way this logic gate works

1353
01:18:26.454 --> 01:18:29.614
is the intracellular signals for the activating CAR.

1354
01:18:29.894 --> 01:18:32.724
These are, everyone knows CD28zeta, 4-1BBzeta.

1355
01:18:33.114 --> 01:18:36.754
These are activating signals, and we have found inhibitory domains that basically

1356
01:18:36.774 --> 01:18:40.694
block those signaling events. So the idea here is not that

1357
01:18:40.914 --> 01:18:43.764
we're preventing the cells from binding, like healthy cells or cancer cells,

1358
01:18:43.894 --> 01:18:47.854
it's the sort of sum of the positive and negative signals that determines

1359
01:18:47.894 --> 01:18:51.494
what the cell does. And I guess going back to interesting NK biology, you

1360
01:18:51.794 --> 01:18:53.404
probably know NK cells do that naturally, right?

1361
01:18:53.414 --> 01:18:57.154
There's a battery of activating and inhibitory receptors, and it's kind of like a

1362
01:18:57.214 --> 01:19:00.174
summation of the two that give you a determination of what it's going to do, and

1363
01:19:00.234 --> 01:19:03.634
we're basically replicating that in a synthetic setting. Okay. Yeah. Thank you.

1364
01:19:03.674 --> 01:19:03.894
Thank you.

1365
01:19:04.814 --> 01:19:06.514
Congratulations. Very nice-

1366
01:19:07.514 --> 01:19:11.474
Thank you ... findings. One thing is when you just give for

1367
01:19:11.554 --> 01:19:15.514
relapsed/refractory AML, just the NK cells by

1368
01:19:15.574 --> 01:19:19.174
themselves, you also get up to 40% remissions. Yeah.

1369
01:19:19.514 --> 01:19:23.044
How do you distinguish what is really an effect of the CAR and what- Yeah ...

1370
01:19:23.074 --> 01:19:25.654
is the NK cell activity by itself? Yeah, it's a great question.

1371
01:19:25.694 --> 01:19:29.294
So I think we have seen studies where you can get responses with native NK cells.

1372
01:19:29.434 --> 01:19:31.894
Typically, in those studies, the durability of those responses are pretty low.

1373
01:19:33.094 --> 01:19:36.754
And so one of the things that we're doing with this particular product is trying to

1374
01:19:36.794 --> 01:19:40.154
demonstrate that we can get deep MRD negative responses that last longer.

1375
01:19:40.334 --> 01:19:43.114
That is also one of the reasons why we went in and actually did this study with the

1376
01:19:43.134 --> 01:19:45.694
CyTOF analysis to show that we are getting target-specific killing.

1377
01:19:46.714 --> 01:19:50.674
Many of those studies, as far as I know, are single studies, single sites,

1378
01:19:50.694 --> 01:19:53.734
and we are trying to do this. This clinical study was done across six different

1379
01:19:53.794 --> 01:19:57.774
clinical centers, and our goal, hopefully, is to have a good

1380
01:19:57.834 --> 01:20:00.054
package around 20, 30 sites that are doing this.

1381
01:20:00.154 --> 01:20:03.194
And this is hopefully also an off-the-shelf frozen product as well.

1382
01:20:03.766 --> 01:20:03.986
Thank you.

1383
01:20:04.006 --> 01:20:04.266
Thank you.

